    excerpt: 'A Fractional CMO is not a consultant who delivers a deck and disappears. Here is exactly what the role covers and how it generates results.',
    content: `<p>If you have ever searched for a Fractional CMO and wondered what you would actually be paying for, you are not alone. The title is common, but the role is widely misunderstood. A Fractional CMO is not a marketing consultant who hands over a strategy document and invoices you. It is an embedded executive who takes ownership of your marketing outcomes on a part-time basis.</p>
<h2>The Core Responsibilities</h2>
<p>A Fractional CMO typically owns four areas: strategy, team leadership, execution oversight, and executive reporting. On the strategy side, they define your positioning, identify your ideal customer profile, prioritize channels, and build the 90-day marketing plan that everything else flows from. On the team side, they manage your internal marketers, coordinate with any agencies you use, and fill the gaps between what your team can do and what needs to get done.</p>
<p>Execution oversight means the Fractional CMO is not just approving work, they are setting quality standards, reviewing campaign performance, making real-time adjustments, and holding the team accountable to outcomes, not just outputs. And at the executive level, they report to your CEO or board, translating marketing performance into business language: revenue contribution, pipeline impact, customer acquisition cost, and market share movement.</p>
<h2>What a Fractional CMO Is Not</h2>
<p>A Fractional CMO is not a freelance marketer who handles execution tasks. They do not write your social media posts, manage your ad accounts, or produce content. If execution is what you need, a marketing coordinator or agency does that work. The Fractional CMO sets the strategy that governs what those people do.</p>
<p>They are also not a short-term project hire. Most Fractional CMO engagements run six to eighteen months because marketing strategy takes time to implement and iterate. The value compounds as the leader learns your business, builds your team, and refines the approach based on performance data.</p>
<h2>Hours and Engagement Structure</h2>
<p>Most Fractional CMO engagements run ten to twenty hours per week. That time is concentrated on high-leverage activities: leadership meetings, strategy sessions, campaign reviews, and executive alignment. Some weeks are heavier, during a product launch or a budget planning cycle, and some are lighter. The engagement is structured around outcomes, not a fixed nine-to-five schedule.</p>
<h2>When the Role Makes Sense</h2>
<p>The Fractional CMO model works best for companies at a specific stage: post-product-market fit, starting to scale, but not yet large enough to justify a full-time CMO at $250,000 to $400,000 per year. Series A to Series C startups, SMBs growing past $5M in revenue, and companies in transition (between CMO hires, post-acquisition, or entering a new market) are the most common clients.</p>
<p>SA Media places Fractional CMOs with companies across Toronto, New York, Dubai, and other markets. The engagements are structured to deliver measurable marketing progress within the first ninety days, with clear KPIs agreed upfront. If your business needs marketing leadership but cannot yet justify the full-time hire, the fractional model is worth a serious look.</p>`,
