    excerpt: 'When a Fractional CMO starts an engagement, they typically find the same five problems. Here is what those problems are and how they get fixed.',
    content: `<p>After working across dozens of growth-stage companies, a pattern emerges: the marketing problems that bring a Fractional CMO into an engagement are almost always a variation on the same five issues. Understanding these recurring problems helps leaders recognize when they are experiencing them, and what it takes to fix them.</p>
<h2>1. No Clear Ideal Customer Profile</h2>
<p>The most common marketing problem in growth-stage companies is trying to serve too many different customer types with the same message. When your ICP is "any company that could use our product," your messaging becomes vague, your channel choices become scattered, and your sales and marketing teams constantly argue about lead quality. A Fractional CMO starts by defining the ICP with enough specificity to be useful: industry, company size, revenue range, key decision-maker titles, triggering events that cause them to look for a solution like yours, and the specific outcome they care about most.</p>
<h2>2. Disconnected Marketing and Sales</h2>
<p>In most companies without strong marketing leadership, the marketing and sales functions are effectively operating separate businesses. Marketing measures success by impressions, followers, and leads generated. Sales measures success by deals closed. Neither team understands what the other needs, and the handoff between them is broken. A Fractional CMO builds the bridge: clear lead qualification criteria, shared pipeline metrics, and an SLA that defines what marketing owes sales and vice versa.</p>
<h2>3. Too Many Channels, None Done Well</h2>
<p>Growth-stage companies frequently spread marketing investment across too many channels simultaneously, LinkedIn, Google Ads, SEO, email, events, podcasts, content, without the team or budget to do any of them properly. The result is mediocre performance everywhere and no clear understanding of what actually drives growth. A Fractional CMO consolidates, picking two or three channels where the ICP actually spends time and investing enough to do those channels well.</p>
<h2>4. Measuring the Wrong Things</h2>
<p>Most marketing dashboards in growth-stage companies track activity (posts published, emails sent, ads running) rather than outcomes (pipeline generated, revenue influenced, customer acquisition cost). A Fractional CMO rebuilds the measurement framework around what leadership actually needs to make decisions: pipeline by source, cost per qualified lead, marketing contribution to revenue, and return on marketing spend.</p>
<h2>5. No Strategic Direction</h2>
<p>The most fundamental problem is the absence of a marketing strategy, a clear answer to the question of where to compete and how to win. Without this, every tactical decision is made in isolation and the cumulative effect of all the marketing activity is less than it should be. The strategy is the first and most important thing a Fractional CMO builds.</p>`,
