    excerpt: 'Many companies hire an agency when they actually need a CMO, and vice versa. Here is how to tell the difference.',
    content: `<p>The choice between a Fractional CMO and a marketing agency is one of the most consequential decisions a growth-stage company makes, and it is one that is frequently made wrong. Companies hire agencies when they need leadership, and then wonder why the campaigns are not working. Or they hire a Fractional CMO when they actually need more execution capacity. Understanding the difference matters.</p>
<h2>What an Agency Does</h2>
<p>A marketing agency provides execution capacity in specific channels: paid media management, SEO and content production, social media management, creative and design, public relations. The agency's value is expertise in a specific discipline and the ability to deploy resources quickly without a full-time hire. Agencies work best when they have clear direction: a strategy to execute, a brief to work from, and a client-side decision-maker who can approve and direct the work.</p>
<p>The agency model breaks down when there is no clear direction. An agency given a vague brief ("grow our brand") will fill the gap with activity, content production, ad campaigns, social posts, that generates outputs without producing meaningful outcomes. This is not the agency's fault; it is a strategic leadership gap.</p>
<h2>What a Fractional CMO Does</h2>
<p>A Fractional CMO provides the strategic leadership that gives agencies something to execute against. They define the positioning, build the channel strategy, set the brief, manage the agency relationship, and hold the agency accountable to business outcomes rather than activity metrics. The Fractional CMO is not a replacement for an agency, they are the reason an agency relationship becomes productive.</p>
<p>A Fractional CMO also does things no agency can: hiring decisions, internal team leadership, budget allocation across all marketing investments, board reporting, and cross-functional alignment with sales, product, and finance.</p>
<h2>How to Decide</h2>
<p>The decision is relatively straightforward: if you know what you want to do and need people to do it, you need an agency. If you do not know what you should be doing or why your current marketing is not working, you need a Fractional CMO first, and likely an agency to support the strategy once it exists. Many of the strongest marketing setups use both: a Fractional CMO providing strategic leadership and one or two specialist agencies providing execution capacity in specific channels.</p>`,
