    date: '2026-02-27',
    category: 'Fractional CTO',
    location: 'General',
    readTime: '7 min',
    excerpt: 'Vendor and platform decisions have long-lasting consequences. Here is the framework an experienced Fractional CTO applies to make them well.',
    content: `<p>Vendor and platform selection decisions are among the most consequential a technology company makes, and among the most poorly documented. Companies choose databases, cloud providers, communication platforms, payment processors, and dozens of other tools that become deeply embedded in their operations, often with minimal structured evaluation and almost no explicit acknowledgment of the long-term implications. A Fractional CTO brings a systematic approach to these decisions that significantly reduces the risk of expensive mistakes.</p>
<h2>The Evaluation Framework</h2>
<p>A Fractional CTO evaluates vendor and platform decisions against five criteria: technical fit (does this tool solve the actual problem in the way we need it solved?), scalability (will this tool continue to work as we grow, in volume, in team size, in geographic footprint?), vendor stability (is the company financially sound and the product actively maintained?), total cost of ownership (what does this tool actually cost when you include implementation, licensing, support, and migration risk?), and lock-in risk (how difficult and expensive would it be to replace this tool if we needed to?).</p>
<h2>The Build vs. Buy Decision</h2>
<p>For every tool or capability, there is an underlying build-buy decision: should we use an existing vendor solution or build this ourselves? The default in most engineering cultures is to build, engineers enjoy building things and tend to underestimate the total cost of building and maintaining custom solutions. A Fractional CTO pushes back on the build default when the vendor solution is adequate, because maintaining custom tooling creates engineering overhead that should be directed toward product differentiation instead.</p>
<h2>Managing Vendor Relationships</h2>
<p>A Fractional CTO also manages the ongoing vendor relationships: ensuring SLAs are met, negotiating contract renewals, evaluating whether the vendor's product evolution continues to meet the company's needs, and making the decision to migrate when a vendor relationship is no longer serving the company well. These are the ongoing operational decisions that determine whether vendor choices continue to be good ones over time, not just at the moment of initial selection.</p>`,
