    excerpt: 'Fintech companies face the most demanding technical requirements in the startup world. Here is how a Fractional CTO navigates them.',
    content: `<p>Fintech is one of the most demanding technical environments in the startup world. The combination of financial data sensitivity, regulatory requirements, real-time processing demands, and the catastrophic cost of security breaches creates a technical leadership challenge that is categorically different from most other sectors. A Fractional CTO who has operated in fintech brings a specific set of frameworks and a risk awareness that is not easily substituted by general technology leadership.</p>
<h2>Regulatory Compliance as a Technical Constraint</h2>
<p>In fintech, regulatory compliance is not a legal or compliance function that sits separately from engineering, it is a fundamental technical constraint that shapes architecture decisions. PCI DSS for payment processing, SOC 2 for enterprise customers, GDPR and CCPA for consumer data, and sector-specific regulations in banking, lending, and investment management all require specific technical controls that need to be designed into the system, not bolted on afterward.</p>
<p>A Fractional CTO with fintech experience begins every architecture review with the regulatory requirements: what data is being processed, what regulations apply to that data, and what technical controls are required to meet those regulations? This sequence, regulatory requirements first, architecture second, prevents the expensive regulatory remediation work that results from building first and thinking about compliance later.</p>
<h2>Security at the Financial Data Standard</h2>
<p>The security standard required for financial data handling is significantly higher than the general technology standard. Encryption at rest and in transit is a baseline requirement, but the requirements extend much further: access controls and audit logging that can satisfy regulatory examination, fraud detection and prevention systems, key management practices, penetration testing requirements, and incident response plans that meet regulatory notification requirements.</p>
<h2>Real-Time Processing at Scale</h2>
<p>Many fintech products require real-time or near-real-time processing: payment authorizations, trading decisions, fraud detection, credit scoring. The architecture that supports these capabilities is fundamentally different from the batch processing architecture that supports most SaaS products, and getting it wrong has direct business and regulatory consequences. A Fractional CTO with real-time systems experience designs the architecture correctly from the start, preventing the expensive migrations that result from building a batch system and later discovering it cannot meet real-time requirements.</p>`,
