    excerpt: 'The first 90 days of a Fractional CTO engagement are the most critical. Here is a detailed breakdown of what should happen and in what sequence.',
    content: `<p>The first ninety days of a Fractional CTO engagement set the foundation for everything that follows. Used well, this period produces a clear technical direction, an improved engineering team dynamic, and early wins that demonstrate the value of the engagement. Used poorly, with too much time spent on orientation and too little on decisive action, the engagement risks losing momentum before it has established credibility.</p>
<h2>Days 1 to 30: Diagnosis</h2>
<p>The first month is diagnostic. The Fractional CTO conducts a comprehensive technical audit: reviewing the codebase, the infrastructure, the development process, the team structure, and the technical backlog. They interview the engineering team individually, meet with the product and business leadership teams, and review any existing technical documentation. The goal is to develop a clear picture of the current technical state, the strengths, the risks, and the priorities, before making any significant recommendations.</p>
<p>During this month, the Fractional CTO also establishes the relationships that will make the engagement effective: the trust of the engineering team, the alignment with the CEO and product leadership, and the understanding of the business context that will govern technical decisions. Getting these relationships right in the first month pays dividends for the duration of the engagement.</p>
<h2>Days 31 to 60: Direction Setting</h2>
<p>The second month is about setting direction. The Fractional CTO presents the results of the technical audit to the leadership team, with a prioritized set of recommendations and a proposed technical roadmap for the next six to twelve months. This is also when the first significant changes are made: technical standards established, quick wins on technical debt addressed, the most urgent security or architecture issues resolved, and any team structure changes implemented.</p>
<p>By the end of day sixty, the engineering team should have a clear sense of direction, the technical roadmap they are building toward and the standards they are working within. This clarity is itself a significant output of the engagement.</p>
<h2>Days 61 to 90: Delivery and Evidence</h2>
<p>The third month shifts the focus to delivery. The first roadmap items are in flight, the team is operating under the new standards, and the Fractional CTO is tracking progress against the roadmap and identifying any obstacles that need to be addressed. The goal of this phase is to produce evidence: tangible demonstrations that the technical investment is producing results. Faster deployment cycles, reduced bug rates, improved infrastructure performance, or the delivery of a key product feature all serve as evidence that the engagement is creating real value.</p>`,
